Augsburg, Bayern, Duitsland","Augsburg, Schwaben, Bayern":"Landkreis Augsburg, Bayern, Duitsland"},"en":{"1318–1343":"1318–1343","1320–1347":"1320–1347","1319–1338":"1319–1338","1338–Female":"1338–Deceased","1340–1411":"1340–1411","1294–1370":"1294–1370","1297–Female":"1297–Deceased","1297":"1297","1340":"1340","1294":"1294","Aft 1338":"after 1338","1370":"1370","10. Februar 1340":"10 February 1340","1338":"1338","about 1318":"about 1318","1347":"1347","about 1338":"about 1338","1411":"1411","1343":"1343","about 1337":"about 1337","1320":"1320","1319":"1319","1318":"1318","Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","Augsburg, Bavaria, Holy Roman Empire":"Bavaria","Augsburg, Bayern, Deutschland":"Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","Augsburg, Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","Augsburg, Schwaben, Bayern":"Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rehm","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernd, Otto, Armin, Hans, Gunter, Hermann, Lothar, Oskar.","German: from the medieval personal name <i>Rehm</i> (see   Remy  ).","German: from Middle High German <i>reme</i> ‘frame, loom, rack’, hence a metonymic occupational name for someone who made or used such items."],"variants":[{"name":"Rahm","meanings":["German:","topographic name from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>rām(e)</i> ‘end, target, mark’, or a habitational name from any of several places in Westphalia and Rhineland named with this word. This surname (in any of the possible senses; see also below) is also found in France (Alsace).","from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>rām</i> ‘soot’, possibly a metonymic occupational name for a blacksmith or charcoal burner, or a nickname for a dirty person."]},{"name":"Rohm","meanings":["German:","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ruom</i> (Old High German <i>hruom</i> ‘fame’), a short form of <i>Ruombald</i> and similar personal names containing this element.","(<b>Röhm</b>): variant of   Rehm  . Compare   Roehm  ."]},{"name":"Rhem","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Rehm   or its variant <b>Remm</b>. This surname is found mainly among African Americans.","History: The progenitor of many of the Rhems was Melcher Rhem (or, as spelled in the surviving documents, <i>Remm</i>) from Germany, who died in 1768 in Craven County, NC. He had three sons, all surnamed <i>Rhem</i>."]},{"name":"Remy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Andre, Jean-Claude, Evens, Germaine, Gisele, Henri, Hugues, Jacques, Jean Raymond, Jean-Daniel, Josee, Laurent.","French (<b>Rémy</b>); West Indian (in Haiti, Martinique, and Guadeloupe <b>Rémy</b>); Walloon and German: from a French personal name which represents a falling together of two distinct Latin names: <i>Remigius</i> (a derivative of <i>remex</i>, genitive <i>remigis</i> ‘rower, oarsman’), and <i>Remedius</i> (from <i>remedium</i> ‘cure, remedy’). The former name was borne by a 6th-century bishop of Rheims; the latter was borne by various other Christian saints of the 8th to 10th centuries. Compare   Ramey  ,   Reamy  , and   Rhamy  .","History: The surname <i>Rémy</i> of French origin is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors, once along with its altered forms <i>Ramey</i> and <i>Remey</i>, and once along with the variant <i>de Rémi</i> and altered forms <i>Reamy</i> and <i>Remey</i>. It is also listed in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America. One of Huguenot ancestors was Jacques Rémy, born <i>c.</i> 1630 in France, who by 1672 lived in Westmoreland County, VA, where he died in 1721. Many of his descendants bear the surname   Ramey  , some also   Rhamy  . — Léopold Rémy <i>dit</i> Bellefleur from Biécourt in the Vosges married Marie-Angélique Trudel in L'Ange-Gardien, QC, in 1758."]},{"name":"Roehm","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Klaus, Eberhard, Gerhard.","German (<b>Röhm</b>): variant of   Rehm  . Compare   Rohm   2."]},{"name":"Rem","meanings":["German: perhaps an altered form of   Rehm  .","American shortened form of Polish <b>Rembowski</b>: unexplained.","Dutch: from the personal name <i>Rem</i>, a short form of   Remmert   or   Rembert  ."]},{"name":"Rehmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","North German: topographic name for someone who lived in a marshy place, from Middle Low German <i>red</i> ‘bog’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’.","North German: variant of   Rehm   2, with the addition of Middle Low German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]}]},{"name":"Johannes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Johannes Rehm I. was born in 1318, in Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany, his father, Berthold Rehm II., was 25 and his mother, Adelheid Stammler von Hut, was 21. He married Anna Langenmantel von Sparren about 1337, in Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany. His occupation is listed as ratsherr, geschlechter in augsburg in Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany. He died in 1343, in his hometown, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1318–1343":"1318–1343","1320–1347":"1320–1347","1319–1338":"1319–1338","1338–Female":"1338–Surnud","1340–1411":"1340–1411","1294–1370":"1294–1370","1297–Female":"1297–Surnud","1297":"1297","1340":"1340","1294":"1294","Aft 1338":"pärast 1338","1370":"1370","10. Februar 1340":"10. veebruar 1340","1338":"1338","about 1318":"umbes 1318","1347":"1347","about 1338":"umbes 1338","1411":"1411","1343":"1343","about 1337":"umbes 13